# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scan-chain
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] The Joint Test Action Group (JTAG) developed a specification for boundary scan testing that was standardized in 1990 as the IEEE Std.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] In 1994, a supplement that contains a description of the boundary scan description language (BSDL) was added which describes the boundary-scan logic content of IEEE Std 1149.1 compliant devices.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Since then, this standard has been adopted by electronic device companies all over the world.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Boundary scan is now mostly synonymous with JTAG.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Each test cell may be programmed via the JTAG scan chain to drive a signal onto a pin and thus across an individual trace on the board; the cell at the destination of the board trace can then be read, verifying that the board trace properly connects the two pins.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] If the trace is shorted to another signal or if the trace is open, the correct signal value does not show up at the destination pin, indicating a fault.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] To provide the boundary scan capability, IC vendors add additional logic to each of their devices, including *scan cells* for each of the external traces.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] These cells are then connected together to form the external boundary scan shift register (BSR), and combined with JTAG Test Access Port (TAP) controller support comprising four (or sometimes more) additional pins plus control circuitry.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Some TAP controllers support scan chains between on-chip logical design blocks, with JTAG instructions which operate on those internal scan chains instead of the BSR.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] This can allow those integrated components to be tested as if they were separate chips on a board.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] On-chip debugging solutions are heavy users of such internal scan chains.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] These designs are part of most Verilog or VHDL libraries.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Overhead for this additional logic is minimal, and generally is well worth the price to enable efficient testing at the board level.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] For normal operation, the added boundary scan latch cells are set so that they have no effect on the circuit, and are therefore effectively invisible.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] However, when the circuit is set into a test mode, the latches enable a data stream to be shifted from one latch into the next.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Once a complete data word has been shifted into the circuit under test, it can be latched into place so it drives external signals.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Shifting the word also generally returns the input values from the signals configured as inputs.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] As the cells can be used to force data into the board, they can set up test conditions.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] The relevant states can then be fed back into the test system by clocking the data word back so that it can be analyzed.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] By adopting this technique, it is possible for a test system to gain test access to a board.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] As most of today's boards are very densely populated with components and tracks, it is very difficult for test systems to physically access the relevant areas of the board to enable them to test the board.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Boundary scan makes access possible without always needing physical probes.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] In modern chip and board design, design for test is a significant issue, and one common design artifact is a set of boundary scan test vectors, possibly delivered in Serial Vector Format (SVF) or a similar interchange format.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Devices communicate to the world via a set of input and output pins.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] By themselves, these pins provide limited visibility into the workings of the device.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] However, devices that support boundary scan contain a shift-register cell for each signal pin of the device.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] These registers are connected in a dedicated path around the device's boundary (hence the name).
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] The path creates a virtual access capability that circumvents the normal inputs and provides direct control of the device and detailed visibility at its outputs.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] The contents of the boundary scan are usually described by the manufacturer using a part-specific BSDL file.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Among other things, a BSDL file will describe each digital signal exposed through pin or ball (depending on the chip packaging) exposed in the boundary scan, as part of its definition of the Boundary Scan Register (BSR).
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] There are JTAG instructions to SAMPLE the data in that boundary scan register, or PRELOAD it with values.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] During testing, I/O signals enter and leave the chip through the boundary-scan cells.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Testing involves a number of test vectors, each of which drives some signals and then verifies that the responses are as expected.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] The boundary-scan cells can be configured to support external testing for interconnection between chips (EXTEST instruction) or internal testing for logic within the chip (INTEST instruction).
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Typically high-end commercial JTAG testing systems allow the import of design 'netlists' from CAD/EDA systems plus the BSDL models of boundary scan/JTAG compliant devices to automatically generate test applications.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] When used during manufacturing, such systems also support non-test but affiliated applications such as in-system programming of various types of flash memory: NOR, NAND, and serial (I2C or SPI).
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Such commercial systems are used by board test professionals and will often cost several thousand dollars for a fully-fledged system.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] They can include diagnostic options to accurately pin-point faults such as open circuits and shorts and may also offer schematic or layout viewers to depict the fault in a graphical manner.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Tests developed with such tools are frequently combined with other test systems such as in-circuit testers (ICTs) or functional board test systems.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] The boundary scan architecture also provides functionality which helps developers and engineers during development stages of an embedded system.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] A JTAG Test Access Port (TAP) can be turned into a low-speed logic analyzer.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] Angell at Stanford University proposed serial testing.
[src:scan-chain/boundary-scan] IBM developed level-sensitive scan design (LSSD).
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Tests are applied at several steps in the hardware manufacturing flow and, for certain products, may also be used for hardware maintenance in the customer's environment.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The tests are generally driven by test programs that execute using automatic test equipment (ATE) or, in the case of system maintenance, inside the assembled system itself.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] In addition to finding and indicating the presence of defects (i.e., the test fails), tests may be able to log diagnostic information about the nature of the encountered test failures.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The diagnostic information can be used to locate the source of the failure.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] In other words, the response of vectors (patterns) from a good circuit is compared with the response of vectors (using the same patterns) from a DUT (device under test).
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] If the response is the same or matches, the circuit is good.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Otherwise, the circuit is not manufactured as intended.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] DFT plays an important role in the development of test programs and as an interface for test applications and diagnostics.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Automatic test pattern generation (ATPG) is much easier if appropriate DFT rules and suggestions have been implemented.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] DFT techniques have been used at least since the early days of electric/electronic data processing equipment.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Early examples from the 1940s/50s are the switches and instruments that allowed an engineer to "scan" (i.e., selectively probe) the voltage/current at some internal nodes in an analog computer [analog scan].
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] DFT often is associated with design modifications that provide improved access to internal circuit elements such that the local internal state can be controlled (controllability) and/or observed (observability) more easily.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The design modifications can be strictly physical in nature (e.g., adding a physical probe point to a net) or add active circuit elements to facilitate controllability/observability (e.g., inserting a multiplexer into a net).
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] While controllability and observability improvements for internal circuit elements definitely are important for test, they are not the only type of DFT.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Other guidelines, for example, deal with the electromechanical characteristics of the interface between the product under test and the test equipment.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Examples are guidelines for the size, shape, and spacing of probe points, or the suggestion to add a high-impedance state to drivers attached to probed nets such that the risk of damage from back-driving is mitigated.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Over the years the industry has developed and used a large variety of more or less detailed and more or less formal guidelines for desired and/or mandatory DFT circuit modifications.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Much of the related body of DFT knowledge focuses on digital circuits, while DFT for analog/mixed-signal circuits takes somewhat of a backseat.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] DFT affects and depends on the methods used for test development, test application, and diagnostics.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Most tool-supported DFT practiced in the industry today, at least for digital circuits, is predicated on a *Structural test* paradigm.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Structural test makes no direct attempt to determine if the overall functionality of the circuit is correct.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Instead, it tries to make sure that the circuit has been assembled correctly from some low-level building blocks as specified in a structural netlist.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] For example, are all specified logic gates present, operating correctly, and connected correctly?
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The stipulation is that if the netlist is correct and structural testing has confirmed the correct assembly of the circuit elements, then the circuit should be functioning correctly.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Note that this is very different from *functional testing*, which attempts to validate that the circuit under test functions according to its functional specification.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] This is closely related to the functional verification problem of determining if the circuit specified by the netlist meets the functional specifications, assuming it is built correctly.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] One benefit of the Structural paradigm is that test generation can focus on testing a limited number of relatively simple circuit elements rather than having to deal with an exponentially exploding multiplicity of functional states and state transitions.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] While the task of testing a single logic gate at a time sounds simple, there is an obstacle to overcome.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] For today's highly complex designs, most gates are deeply embedded whereas the test equipment is only connected to the primary Input/outputs (I/Os) and/or some physical test points.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The embedded gates, hence, must be manipulated through intervening layers of logic.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] If the intervening logic contains state elements, then the issue of an exponentially exploding state space and state transition sequencing creates an unsolvable problem for test generation.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] To simplify test generation, DFT addresses the accessibility problem by removing the need for complicated state transition sequences when trying to control and/or observe what's happening at some internal circuit element.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Depending on the DFT choices made during circuit design/implementation, the generation of Structural tests for complex logic circuits can be more or less automated or self-automated.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] One key objective of DFT methodologies, hence, is to allow designers to make trade-offs between the amount and type of DFT and the cost/benefit (time, effort, quality) of the test generation task.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Another benefit is to diagnose a circuit in case any problem emerges in the future.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] It is like adding some features or provisions in the design so that devices can be tested in case of any fault during its use.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] One challenge for the industry is keeping up with the rapid advances in chip technology (I/O count/size/placement/spacing, I/O speed, internal circuit count/speed/power, thermal control, etc.) without being forced to continually upgrade the test equipment.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Modern DFT techniques, hence, have to offer options that allow next-generation chips and assemblies to be tested on existing test equipment and/or reduce the requirements/cost for new test equipment.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] As a result, DFT techniques are continually being updated, such as incorporation of compression, in order to make sure that tester application times stay within certain bounds dictated by the cost target for the products under test.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Especially for advanced semiconductor technologies, it is expected that some of the chips on each manufactured wafer contain defects that render them non-functional.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The primary objective of testing is to find and separate those non-functional chips from the fully functional ones, meaning that one or more responses captured by the tester from a non-functional chip under test differ from the expected response.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The percentage of chips that fail testing, hence, should be closely related to the expected functional yield for that chip type.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] In reality, however, it is not uncommon that all chips of a new chip type arriving at the test floor for the first time fail (so-called zero-yield situation).
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] In that case, the chips have to go through a debug process that tries to identify the reason for the zero-yield situation.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] In other cases, the test fall-out (percentage of test failures) may be higher than expected/acceptable or fluctuate suddenly.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Again, the chips have to be subjected to an analysis process to identify the reason for the excessive test fall-out.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] In both cases, vital information about the nature of the underlying problem may be hidden in the way the chips fail during testing.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] To facilitate better analysis, additional failure information beyond a simple pass/fail is collected into a fail log.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The fail log typically contains information about when (e.g., tester cycle), where (e.g., at what tester channel), and how (e.g., logic value) the test failed.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Diagnostics attempt to derive from the fail log at which logical/physical location inside the chip the problem most likely started.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] By running a large number of failures through the diagnostics process, called volume diagnostics, systematic failures can be identified.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] In some cases (e.g., printed circuit boards, multi-chip modules (MCMs), embedded or stand-alone memories) it may be possible to repair a failing circuit under test.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] For that purpose, diagnostics must quickly find the failing unit and create a work order for repairing or replacing the failing unit.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] DFT approaches can be more or less diagnostics-friendly.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The related objectives of DFT are to facilitate or simplify failure data collection and diagnostics to an extent that can enable intelligent failure analysis (FA) sample selection, as well as improve the cost, accuracy, speed, and throughput of diagnostics and FA.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The most common method for delivering test data from chip inputs to internal *circuits under test* (CUTs, for short), and observing their outputs, is called scan-design.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] In scan design, registers (flip-flops or latches) in the design are connected in one or more scan chains, which are used to gain access to internal nodes of the chip.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Test patterns are shifted in via the scan chain(s), functional clock signals are pulsed to test the circuit during the "capture cycle(s)", and the results are then shifted out to chip output pins and compared against the expected "good machine" results.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Straightforward application of scan techniques can result in large vector sets with corresponding long tester time and memory requirements.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Test compression techniques address this problem by decompressing the scan input on chip and compressing the test output.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Large gains are possible since any particular test vector usually only needs to set and/or examine a small fraction of the scan chain bits.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The output of a scan design may be provided in forms such as Serial Vector Format (SVF), to be executed by test equipment.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] In addition to being useful for manufacturing "go/no go" testing, scan chains can also be used to "debug" chip designs.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] In this context, the chip is exercised in normal "functional mode" (for example, a computer or mobile phone chip might execute assembly language instructions).
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] At any time, the chip clock can be stopped, and the chip re-configured into "test mode".
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] At this point, the full internal state can be dumped out or set to any desired values by use of the scan chains.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] Another use of scan to aid debugging consists of scanning in an initial state to all memory elements and then go back to functional mode to perform system debugging.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] The advantage is to bring the system to a known state without going through many clock cycles.
[src:scan-chain/design-for-testing] This use of scan chains, along with the clock control circuits, is a related sub-discipline of logic design called *design for debug* or *design for debuggability*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In electronics, **flip-flops** and **latches** are circuits that have two stable states that can store state information – a bistable multivibrator.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The circuit can be made to change state by signals applied to one or more control inputs and will output its state (often along with its logical complement).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] It is the basic storage element in sequential logic.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops and latches are fundamental building blocks of digital electronics systems used in computers, communications, and many other types of systems.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops and latches are used as data storage elements to store a single *bit* (binary digit) of data; one of its two states represents a *one* and the other represents a *zero*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Such data storage can be used for storage of *state*, and such a circuit is described as sequential logic in electronics.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When used in a finite-state machine, the output and next state depend not only on its current input, but also on its current state (and hence, previous inputs).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] It can also be used for counting of pulses, and for synchronizing variably-timed input signals to some reference timing signal.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The term flip-flop has historically referred generically to both level-triggered (asynchronous, transparent, or opaque) and edge-triggered (synchronous, or clocked) circuits that store a single bit of data using gates.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Modern authors reserve the term *flip-flop* exclusively for edge-triggered storage elements and *latches* for level-triggered ones.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The terms *edge-triggered*, and *level-triggered* may be used to avoid ambiguity.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When a level-triggered latch is enabled, it becomes transparent, but an edge-triggered flip-flop's output only changes on a clock edge (either positive going or negative going).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Different types of flip-flops and latches are available as integrated circuits, usually with multiple elements per chip.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] For example, 74HC75 is a quadruple transparent latch in the 7400 series.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The first electronic latch was invented in 1918 by the British physicists William Eccles and F.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] It was initially called the *Eccles–Jordan trigger circuit* and consisted of two active elements (vacuum tubes).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The design was used in the 1943 British Colossus codebreaking computer and such circuits and their transistorized versions were common in computers even after the introduction of integrated circuits, though latches and flip-flops made from logic gates are also common now.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Early latches were known variously as trigger circuits or multivibrators.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] They differ slightly from some of the definitions given below.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Lindley explains that he heard the story of the JK flip-flop from Eldred Nelson, who is responsible for coining the term while working at Hughes Aircraft.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops in use at Hughes at the time were all of the type that came to be known as J-K.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In designing a logical system, Nelson assigned letters to flip-flop inputs as follows: #1: A & B, #2: C & D, #3: E & F, #4: G & H, #5: J & K.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Nelson used the notations *j-input* and *k-input* in a patent application filed in 1953.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Transparent or asynchronous latches can be built around a single pair of cross-coupled inverting elements: vacuum tubes, bipolar transistors, field-effect transistors, inverters, and inverting logic gates have all been used in practical circuits.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Clocked flip-flops are specially designed for synchronous systems; such devices ignore their inputs except at the transition of a dedicated clock signal (known as clocking, pulsing, or strobing).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Clocking causes the flip-flop either to change or to retain its output signal based upon the values of the input signals at the transition.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Some flip-flops change output on the rising edge of the clock, others on the falling edge.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Since the elementary amplifying stages are inverting, two stages can be connected in succession (as a cascade) to form the needed non-inverting amplifier.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In this configuration, each amplifier may be considered as an active inverting feedback network for the other inverting amplifier.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Thus the two stages are connected in a non-inverting loop although the circuit diagram is usually drawn as a symmetric cross-coupled pair (both the drawings are initially introduced in the Eccles–Jordan patent).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops and latches can be divided into common types: SR (set-reset), D (data), T (toggle), and JK (see History section above).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The behavior of a particular type can be described by the characteristic equation that derives the *next* output (*Q*next) in terms of the input signal(s) and/or the current output, Q .
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When using static gates as building blocks, the most fundamental latch is the asynchronous *set-reset (SR) latch*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Its two inputs S and R can set the internal state to 1 using the combination S=1 and R=0, and can reset the internal state to 0 using the combination S=0 and R=1.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The SR latch can be constructed from a pair of cross-coupled NOR or NAND logic gates.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The stored bit is present on the output marked Q.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] It is convenient to think of NAND, NOR, AND and OR as controlled operations, where one input is chosen as the control input set and the other bit as the input to be processed depending on the state of the control.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Essentially, they can all be used as switches that either set a specific value or let an input value pass.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The SR NOR latch consists of two parallel NOR gates where the output of each NOR is also fanned out into one input of the other NOR, as shown in the figure.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] We call these output-to-input connections *feedback inputs*, or simply *feedbacks*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The remaining inputs we will use as *control* inputs as explained above.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Notice that at this point, because everything is symmetric, it does not matter to which inputs the outputs are connected.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] We now break the symmetry by choosing which of the remaining control inputs will be our set and reset and we can call *set NOR* the NOR gate with the set control and *reset NOR* the NOR with the reset control; in the figures the set NOR is the bottom one and the reset NOR is the top one.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The output of the reset NOR will be our stored bit Q, while we will see that the output of the set NOR stores its complement Q.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] To derive the behavior of the SR NOR latch, consider S and R as control inputs and remember that, from the equations above, set and reset NOR with control 1 will fix their outputs to 0, while set and reset NOR with control 0 will act as a NOT gate.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The R = S = 1 combination is called a **restricted combination** or a **forbidden state** because, as both NOR gates then output zeros, it breaks the logical equation Q = **not** Q.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The combination is also inappropriate in circuits where *both* inputs may go low *simultaneously* (i.e. a transition from *restricted* to *hold*).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The output could remain in a metastable state and may eventually lock at either 1 or 0 depending on the propagation time relations between the gates (a race condition).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] To overcome the restricted combination, one can add gates to the inputs that would convert `(S, R) = (1, 1)` to one of the non-restricted combinations.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This is done in nearly every programmable logic controller.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Alternatively, the restricted combination can be made to *toggle* the output.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The circuit shown below is a basic NAND latch.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The inputs are also generally designated S and R for Set and Reset respectively.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Because the NAND inputs must normally be logic 1 to avoid affecting the latching action, the inputs are considered to be inverted in this circuit (or active low).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The circuit uses the same feedback as SR NOR, just replacing NOR gates with NAND gates, to *remember* and retain its logical state even after the controlling input signals have changed.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Again, recall that a 1-controlled NAND always outputs 0, while a 0-controlled NAND acts as a NOT gate.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When the S and R inputs are both high, feedback maintains the Q outputs to the previous state.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When either is zero, they fix their output bits to 0 while to other adapts to the complement.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] From a teaching point of view, SR latches drawn as a pair of cross-coupled components (transistors, gates, tubes, etc.) are often hard to understand for beginners.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] A didactically easier explanation is to draw the latch as a single feedback loop instead of the cross-coupling.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The following is an SR latch built with an AND gate with one inverted input and an OR gate.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Note that the inverter is not needed for the latch functionality, but rather to make both inputs high-active.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Note that the SR AND-OR latch has the benefit that S = 1, R = 1 is well defined.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In above version of the SR AND-OR latch it gives priority to the R signal over the S signal.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] If priority of S over R is needed, this can be achieved by connecting output Q to the output of the OR gate instead of the output of the AND gate.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The SR AND-OR latch is easier to understand, because both gates can be explained in isolation, again with the control view of AND and OR from above.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When neither S or R is set, then both the OR gate and the AND gate are in "hold mode", i.e., they let the input through, their output is the input from the feedback loop.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When input S = 1, then the OR gate outputs 1, regardless of the other input from the feedback loop ("set mode").
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When input R = 1 then the AND gate outputs 0, regardless of the other input from the feedback loop ("reset mode").
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] And since the AND gate takes the output of the OR gate as input, R has priority over S.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Latches drawn as cross-coupled gates may look less intuitive, as the behavior of one gate appears to be intertwined with the other gate.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The standard NOR or NAND latches could also be re-drawn with the feedback loop, but in their case the feedback loop does not show the same signal value throughout the whole feedback loop.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] However, the SR AND-OR latch has the drawback that it would need an extra inverter, if an inverted Q output is needed.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The JK latch is much less frequently used than the JK flip-flop.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Hence, the JK latch is an SR latch that is made to *toggle* its output (oscillate between 0 and 1) when passed the input combination of 11.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Unlike the JK flip-flop, the 11 input combination for the JK latch is not very useful because there is no clock that directs toggling.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Latches are designed to be *transparent.* That is, input signal changes cause immediate changes in output.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Additional logic can be added to a transparent latch to make it *non-transparent* or *opaque* when another input (an *enable* input) is not asserted.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] A periodic *enable* input signal may be called a *write strobe*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When the *enable* input is a clock signal, the latch is said to be **level-sensitive** (to the level of the clock signal), as opposed to **edge-sensitive** like flip-flops below.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When several *transparent* latches follow each other, if they are all transparent at the same time, signals will propagate through them all.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] However, following a *transparent-high* latch by a *transparent-low* latch (or vice-versa) causes the state and output to only change on clock edges, forming what is called a *master–slave flip-flop*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] A *gated SR latch* can be made by adding a second level of NAND gates to an *inverted SR latch*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The extra NAND gates further invert the inputs so a *SR latch* becomes a *gated SR latch* (a *SR latch* would transform into a *gated SR latch* with inverted enable).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Alternatively, a *gated SR latch* (with non-inverting enable) can be made by adding a second level of AND gates to a *SR latch*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] With E high (*enable* true), the signals can pass through the input gates to the encapsulated latch; all signal combinations except for (0, 0) = *hold* then immediately reproduce on the (Q, Q) output, i.e. the latch is *transparent*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] With E low (*enable* false) the latch is *closed (opaque)* and remains in the state it was left the last time E was high.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This latch exploits the fact that, in the two active input combinations (01 and 10) of a gated SR latch, R is the complement of S.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The input NAND stage converts the two D input states (0 and 1) to these two input combinations for the next SR latch by inverting the data input signal.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The low state of the *enable* signal produces the inactive *11* combination.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Thus a gated D-latch may be considered as a *one-input synchronous SR latch*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This configuration prevents application of the restricted input combination.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] It is also known as *transparent latch*, *data latch*, or simply *gated latch*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] It has a *data* input and an *enable* signal (sometimes named *clock*, or *control*).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The word *transparent* comes from the fact that, when the enable input is on, the signal propagates directly through the circuit, from the input D to the output Q.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Gated D-latches are also **level-sensitive** with respect to the level of the clock or enable signal.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Transparent latches are typically used as I/O ports or in asynchronous systems, or in synchronous two-phase systems (synchronous systems that use a two-phase clock), where two latches operating on different clock phases prevent data transparency as in a master–slave flip-flop.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The truth table below shows that when the *e*nable input is 0, the D input has no effect on the output.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The classic gated latch designs have some undesirable characteristics.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] They require dual-rail logic or an inverter.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The input-to-output propagation may take up to three gate delays.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The input-to-output propagation is not constant – some outputs take two gate delays while others take three.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] A successful alternative is the Earle latch.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] It requires only a single data input, and its output takes a constant two gate delays.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In addition, the two gate levels of the Earle latch can, in some cases, be merged with the last two gate levels of the circuits driving the latch because many common computational circuits have an OR layer followed by an AND layer as their last two levels.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Merging the latch function can implement the latch with no additional gate delays.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The merge is commonly exploited in the design of pipelined computers, and, in fact, was originally developed by John G.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Earle to be used in the IBM System/360 Model 91 for that purpose.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] If the middle NAND gate is omitted, then one gets the **polarity hold latch**, which is commonly used because it demands less logic.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] However, it is susceptible to logic hazard.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Intentionally skewing the clock signal can avoid the hazard.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The D flip-flop is widely used, and known as a *data* flip-flop.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The D flip-flop captures the value of the D-input at a definite portion of the clock cycle (such as the rising edge of the clock).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] That captured value becomes the Q output.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] At other times, the output Q does not change.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The D flip-flop can be viewed as a memory cell, a zero-order hold, or a delay line.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Most D-type flip-flops in ICs have the capability to be forced to the set or reset state (which ignores the D and clock inputs).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Usually, the S = R = 1 condition (illegal in SR latches) is resolved in D-type flip-flops.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Setting S = R = 0 makes the flip-flop behave as described above.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] These flip-flops are very useful, as they form the basis for shift registers, which are an essential part of many electronic devices.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The advantage of the D flip-flop over the D-type *transparent latch* is that the signal on the D input pin is captured the moment the flip-flop is clocked, and subsequent changes on the D input will be ignored until the next clock event.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] An exception is that some flip-flops have a *reset* signal input, which will reset Q (to zero), and may be either asynchronous or synchronous with the clock.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The above circuit shifts the contents of the register to the right, one bit position on each active transition of the clock.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The input X is shifted into the leftmost bit position.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This circuit consists of two stages implemented by SR NAND latches.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The input stage (the two latches on the left) processes the clock and data signals to ensure correct input signals for the output stage (the single latch on the right).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] If the clock is low, both the output signals of the input stage are high regardless of the data input; the output latch is unaffected and it stores the previous state.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When the clock signal changes from low to high, only one of the output voltages (depending on the data signal) goes low and sets/resets the output latch: if D = 0, the lower output becomes low; if D = 1, the upper output becomes low.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] As long as the clock signal stays high, these input-stage outputs keep their states regardless of the data input and force the output latch to stay in the corresponding state, as the input logical zero (of the output stage) remains active while the clock is high.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Any change of the data input while the clock is high will not change the states of the two input-stage latches.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Hence the role of the output latch is to store the data only while the clock is low.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The circuit is closely related to the gated D latch as both the circuits convert the two D input states (0 and 1) to two input combinations (01 and 10) for the output SR latch by inverting the data input signal (both the circuits split the single D signal in two complementary S and R signals).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The difference is that NAND logical gates are used in the gated D latch, while SR NAND latches are used in the positive-edge-triggered D flip-flop.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The role of these latches is to *lock* the active output producing low voltage (a logical zero); thus the positive-edge-triggered D flip-flop can also be thought of as a gated D latch with latched input gates.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] A master–slave D flip-flop is created by connecting two gated D latches in series, and inverting the *enable* input to one of them.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] For a positive-edge triggered master–slave D flip-flop, when the clock signal is low (logical 0) the *enable* seen by the first or *master* D latch (the inverted clock signal) is high (logical 1).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This allows the *master* latch to store the input value when the clock signal transitions from low to high.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] As the clock signal goes high (0 to 1) the inverted *enable* of the first latch goes low (1 to 0) and the value seen at the input to the master latch is *locked*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Nearly simultaneously, the twice inverted *enable* of the second or *slave* D latch transitions from low to high (0 to 1) with the clock signal.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This allows the signal captured at the rising edge of the clock by the now *locked* master latch to pass through the *slave* latch.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When the clock signal returns to low (1 to 0), the output of the *slave* latch is *locked*, and the value seen at the last rising edge of the clock is held while the *master* latch begins to accept new values in preparation for the next rising clock edge.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Removing the leftmost inverter in the circuit creates a D-type flip-flop that captures the D input on the *falling edge* of the clock signal.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-Flops that read in a new value on the rising and the falling edge of the clock are called dual-edge-triggered flip-flops.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Such a flip-flop may be built using two single-edge-triggered D-type flip-flops and a multiplexer, or by using two single-edge triggered D-type flip-flops and three XOR gates.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] An efficient functional alternative to a D flip-flop can be made with dynamic circuits (where information is stored in a capacitance) as long as it is clocked often enough; while not a true flip-flop, it is still called a flip-flop for its functional role.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] While the master–slave D element is triggered on the edge of a clock, its components are each triggered by clock levels.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The *edge-triggered D flip-flop*, as it is called even though it is not a true flip-flop, does not have the master–slave properties.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Edge-triggered D flip-flops are often implemented in integrated high-speed operations using dynamic logic.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This means that the digital output is stored on parasitic device capacitance while the device is not transitioning.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This design facilitates resetting by simply discharging one or more internal nodes.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] A common dynamic flip-flop variety is the true single-phase clock (TSPC) type which performs the flip-flop operation with little power and at high speeds.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] However, dynamic flip-flops will typically not work at static or low clock speeds: given enough time, leakage paths may discharge the parasitic capacitance enough to cause the flip-flop to enter invalid states.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] If the T input is high, the T flip-flop changes state ("toggles") on the triggering clock edge.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] If the T input is low, the flip-flop holds the previous value.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When T is held high, the toggle flip-flop divides the clock frequency by two; that is, if clock frequency is 4 MHz, the output frequency obtained from the flip-flop will be 2 MHz.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This "divide by" feature has application in various types of digital counters.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] A T flip-flop can also be built using a JK flip-flop (J & K pins are connected together and act as T) or a D flip-flop (T input XOR Qprevious drives the D input).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The JK flip-flop behaves like an edge-triggered SR flip-flop (J: Set, K: Reset) that replaces the illegal S = R = 1 condition with a *flip* or toggle command.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Setting J = K = 0 maintains the current state.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The JK flip-flop is considered a universal flip-flop, because it can be configured to work as an SR flip-flop, a D flip-flop, or a T flip-flop.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] For instance, to synthesize a D flip-flop, simply set K equal to the complement of J (input J will act as input D).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Similarly, to synthesize a T flip-flop, set K equal to J.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The input must be held steady in a period around the rising edge of the clock known as the aperture.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Imagine taking a picture of a frog on a lily pad.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Suppose the frog then jumps into the water.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] If you take a picture of the frog as it jumps into the water, you will get a blurry picture of the frog jumping into the water—it's not clear which state the frog was in.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] But if you take a picture while the frog sits steadily on the pad (or is steadily in the water), you will get a clear picture.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In the same way, the input to a flip-flop must be held steady during the *aperture* of the flip-flop.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Short impulses applied to asynchronous inputs (set, reset) should not be applied completely within the recovery-removal period, or else it becomes entirely indeterminable whether the flip-flop will transition to the appropriate state.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In another case, where an asynchronous signal simply makes one transition that happens to fall between the recovery/removal time, eventually the flip-flop will transition to the appropriate state, but a very short glitch may or may not appear on the output, dependent on the synchronous input signal.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This second situation may or may not have significance to a circuit design.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Set and Reset (and other) signals may be either synchronous or asynchronous and therefore may be characterized with either Setup/Hold or Recovery/Removal times, and synchronicity is very dependent on the design of the flip-flop.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Differentiation between Setup/Hold and Recovery/Removal times is often necessary when verifying the timing of larger circuits because asynchronous signals may be found to be less critical than synchronous signals.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The differentiation offers circuit designers the ability to define the verification conditions for these types of signals independently.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops are subject to a problem called metastability, which can happen when two inputs, such as data and clock or clock and reset, are changing at about the same time.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When the order is not clear, within appropriate timing constraints, the result is that the output may behave unpredictably, taking many times longer than normal to settle to one state or the other, or even oscillating several times before settling.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Theoretically, the time to settle down is not bounded.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The metastability in flip-flops can be avoided by ensuring that the data and control inputs are held valid and constant for specified periods before and after the clock pulse, called the **setup time** (tsu) and the **hold time** (th) respectively.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] These times are specified in the data sheet for the device, and are typically between a few nanoseconds and a few hundred picoseconds for modern devices.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Depending upon the flip-flop's internal organization, it is possible to build a device with a zero (or even negative) setup or hold time requirement but not both simultaneously.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Unfortunately, it is not always possible to meet the setup and hold criteria, because the flip-flop may be connected to a real-time signal that could change at any time, outside the control of the designer.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In this case, the best the designer can do is to reduce the probability of error to a certain level, depending on the required reliability of the circuit.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] One technique for suppressing metastability is to connect two or more flip-flops in a chain, so that the output of each one feeds the data input of the next, and all devices share a common clock.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] With this method, the probability of a metastable event can be reduced to a negligible value, but never to zero.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The probability of metastability gets closer and closer to zero as the number of flip-flops connected in series is increased.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The number of flip-flops being cascaded is referred to as the *ranking*; *dual-ranked* flip flops (two flip-flops in series) is a common situation.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] So-called metastable-hardened flip-flops are available, which work by reducing the setup and hold times as much as possible, but even these cannot eliminate the problem entirely.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This is because metastability is more than simply a matter of circuit design.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] When the transitions in the clock and the data are close together in time, the flip-flop is forced to decide which event happened first.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] However fast the device is made, there is always the possibility that the input events will be so close together that it cannot detect which one happened first.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] It is therefore logically impossible to build a perfectly metastable-proof flip-flop.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops are sometimes characterized for a maximum settling time (the maximum time they will remain metastable under specified conditions).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In this case, dual-ranked flip-flops that are clocked slower than the maximum allowed metastability time will provide proper conditioning for asynchronous (e.g., external) signals.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Another important timing value for a flip-flop is the clock-to-output delay (common symbol in data sheets: tCO) or propagation delay (tP), which is the time a flip-flop takes to change its output after the clock edge.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The time for a high-to-low transition (tPHL) is sometimes different from the time for a low-to-high transition (tPLH).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This relationship between tCO and th is normally guaranteed if the flip-flops are physically identical.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Furthermore, for correct operation, it is easy to verify that the clock period has to be greater than the sum tsu + th.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Flip-flops can be generalized in at least two ways: by making them 1-of-N instead of 1-of-2, and by adapting them to logic with more than two states.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In the special cases of 1-of-3 encoding, or multi-valued ternary logic, such an element may be referred to as a *flip-flap-flop*.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In a conventional flip-flop, exactly one of the two complementary outputs is high.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] This can be generalized to a memory element with N outputs, exactly one of which is high (alternatively, where exactly one of N is low).
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The output is therefore always a one-hot (respectively *one-cold*) representation.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] The construction is similar to a conventional cross-coupled flip-flop; each output, when high, inhibits all the other outputs.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Alternatively, more or less conventional flip-flops can be used, one per output, with additional circuitry to make sure only one at a time can be true.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] Another generalization of the conventional flip-flop is a memory element for multi-valued logic.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In this case the memory element retains exactly one of the logic states until the control inputs induce a change.
[src:scan-chain/flip-flop-electronics] In addition, a multiple-valued clock can also be used, leading to new possible clock transitions.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] JTAG implements standards for on-chip instrumentation in electronic design automation (EDA) as a complementary tool to digital simulation.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] It specifies the use of a dedicated debug port implementing a serial communications interface for low-overhead access without requiring direct external access to the system address and data buses.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The interface connects to an on-chip **Test Access Port** (TAP) that implements a stateful protocol to access a set of test registers that present chip logic levels and device capabilities of various parts.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The Joint Test Action Group formed in 1985 to develop a method of verifying designs and testing printed circuit boards after manufacture.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In 1990, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers codified the results of the effort in IEEE Standard 1149.1-1990, entitled *Standard Test Access Port and Boundary-Scan Architecture*.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The JTAG standards have been extended by multiple semiconductor chip manufacturers with specialized variants to provide vendor-specific features.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In the 1980s, multi-layer circuit boards and integrated circuits (ICs) using ball grid array and similar mounting technologies were becoming standard, and connections were being made between ICs that were not available to probes.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The majority of manufacturing and field faults in circuit boards were due to poor solder joints on the boards, imperfections among board connections, or the bonds and bond wires from IC pads to pin lead frames.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The Joint Test Action Group (JTAG) was formed in 1985 to provide a pins-out view from one IC pad to another so these faults could be discovered.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The industry standard became an IEEE standard in 1990 as IEEE Std.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In the same year, Intel released their first processor with JTAG (the 80486), which led to quicker industry adoption by all manufacturers.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In 1994, a supplement that contains a description of the boundary scan description language (BSDL) was added.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Further refinements regarding the use of all-zeros for EXTEST, separating the use of SAMPLE from PRELOAD and better implementation for OBSERVE_ONLY cells were made and released in 2001.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Since 1990, this standard has been adopted by electronics companies around the world.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Boundary scan is now mostly synonymous with JTAG, but JTAG has essential uses beyond such manufacturing applications.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] 1149.1 has introduced a vast set of optional features, associated extensions to BSDL, and a new procedural description language (PDL) based on Tcl.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Although JTAG's early applications targeted board-level testing, here the JTAG standard was designed to assist with device, board, and system testing, diagnosis, and fault isolation.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Today JTAG is used as the primary means of accessing sub-blocks of integrated circuits, making it an essential mechanism for debugging embedded systems which might not have any other debug-capable communications channel.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] On most systems, JTAG-based debugging is available from the very first instruction after CPU reset, letting it assist with development of early boot software which runs before anything is set up.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] An in-circuit emulator (or, more correctly, a *JTAG adapter*) uses JTAG as the transport mechanism to access on-chip debug modules inside the target CPU.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Those modules let software developers debug the software of an embedded system directly at the machine instruction level when needed, or (more typically) in terms of high-level language source code.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] System software debug support is for many software developers the main reason to be interested in JTAG.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Multiple silicon architectures, such as PowerPC, MIPS, ARM, and x86, built an entire software debug, instruction tracing, and data tracing infrastructure around the basic JTAG protocol.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Frequently, individual silicon vendors, however, only implement parts of these extensions.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Some examples are ARM CoreSight and Nexus as well as Intel's BTS (Branch Trace Storage), LBR (Last Branch Record), and IPT (Intel Processor Trace) implementations.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] There are a number of other such silicon vendor-specific extensions that may not be documented except under NDA.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The adoption of the JTAG standard helped move JTAG-centric debugging environments away from early processor-specific designs.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Processors can normally be halted, single stepped, or let run freely.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] One can set code breakpoints, both for code in RAM (often using a special machine instruction e.g., INT3) and in ROM/flash.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Data breakpoints are often available, as is bulk data download to RAM.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Most designs have *halt mode debugging*, but some allow debuggers to access registers and data buses without needing to halt the core being debugged.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Sometimes FPGA developers also use JTAG to develop debugging tools.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The same JTAG techniques used to debug software running inside a CPU can help debug other digital design blocks inside an FPGA.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] For example, custom JTAG instructions can be provided to allow reading registers built from arbitrary sets of signals inside the FPGA, providing visibility for behaviors that are invisible to boundary scan operations.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Similarly, writing such registers could provide controllability that is not otherwise available.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] JTAG allows device programmer hardware to transfer data into internal non-volatile device memory (e.g., CPLDs).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Some device programmers serve a double purpose for programming as well as debugging the device.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In the case of FPGAs, volatile memory devices can also be programmed via the JTAG port, normally during development work.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In addition, internal monitoring capabilities (temperature, voltage, and current) may be accessible via the JTAG port.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] JTAG programmers are also used to write software and data into flash memory.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] This is usually done using the same data bus access the CPU would use, and is sometimes handled by the CPU.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In other cases, the memory chips themselves have JTAG interfaces.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Some modern debug architectures provide internal and external bus master access without needing to halt and take over a CPU.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In the worst case, it is usually possible to drive external bus signals using the boundary scan facility.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] As a practical matter, when developing an embedded system, emulating the instruction store is the fastest way to implement the *debug cycle* (edit, compile, download, test, and debug).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] This is because the in-circuit emulator simulating an instruction store can be updated very quickly from the development host via, say, USB.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Using a serial UART port and bootloader to upload firmware to Flash makes this debug cycle quite slow and possibly expensive in terms of tools; installing firmware into Flash (or SRAM instead of Flash) via JTAG is an intermediate solution between these extremes.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] JTAG boundary scan technology provides access to a number of logic signals of a complex integrated circuit, including the device pins.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The signals are represented in the boundary scan register (BSR) accessible via the TAP.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] This permits testing as well as controlling the states of the signals for testing and debugging.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Therefore, both software and hardware (manufacturing) faults may be located and an operating device may be monitored.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] When combined with built-in self-test (BIST), the JTAG scan chain enables a low-overhead embedded solution to test an IC for certain static faults (shorts, opens, and logic errors).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The scan chain mechanism does not generally help diagnose or test for timing, temperature or other dynamic operational errors that may occur.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Test cases are often provided in standardized formats such as SVF, or its binary sibling XSVF, and used in production tests.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The ability to perform such testing on finished boards is an essential part of Design For Test in today's products, increasing the number of faults that can be found before products ship to customers.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] A JTAG interface is a special interface added to a chip.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Depending on the version of JTAG, two, four, or five pins are added.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The four and five-pin interfaces are designed so that multiple chips on a board can have their JTAG lines daisy-chained together if specific conditions are met.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The two-pin interface is designed so that multiple chips can be connected in a star topology.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In either case, a test probe needs only connect to a single JTAG port to have access to all chips on a circuit board.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The TRST pin is an optional active-low reset to the test logic, usually asynchronous, but sometimes synchronous, depending on the chip.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] If the pin is not available, the test logic can be reset by switching to the reset state synchronously, using TCK and TMS.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Note that resetting test logic doesn't necessarily imply resetting anything else.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] There are generally some processor-specific JTAG operations that can reset all or part of the chip being debugged.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Since only one data line is available, the protocol is serial.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] One bit of data is transferred in from TDI and out to TDO per TCK rising clock edge.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Instructions for typical ICs might read the chip ID, sample input pins, drive (or float) output pins, manipulate chip functions, or bypass (pipe TDI to TDO to logically shorten chains of multiple chips).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] As with any clocked signal, data presented to TDI must be valid for some chip-specific *Setup* time before and *Hold* time after the relevant (here, rising) clock edge.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] TDO data is valid for some chip-specific time after the falling edge of TCK.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The maximum operating frequency of TCK varies depending on all chips in the chain (the lowest speed must be used), but it is typically 10-100 MHz (100-10 ns per bit).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Also, TCK frequencies depend on board layout and JTAG adapter capabilities and state.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] One chip might have a 40 MHz JTAG clock, but only if it is using a 200 MHz clock for non-JTAG operations; and it might need to use a much slower clock when it is in a low-power mode.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Accordingly, some JTAG adapters have *adaptive clocking* using an RTCK (Return TCK) signal.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Faster TCK frequencies are most useful when JTAG is used to transfer large amounts of data, such as when storing a program executable into flash memory.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Clocking changes on TMS steps through a standardized JTAG state machine.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The JTAG state machine can reset, access an instruction register, or access data selected by the instruction register.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] JTAG platforms often add signals to the handful defined by the IEEE 1149.1 specification.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] A System Reset (SRST) signal is quite common, letting debuggers reset the whole system, not just the parts with JTAG support.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Sometimes, there are event signals used to trigger activity by the host or by the device being monitored through JTAG, or, perhaps, additional control lines.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Even though few consumer products provide an explicit JTAG port connector, the connections are often available on the printed circuit board as a remnant from development prototyping and/or production.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] When exploited, these connections often provide the most viable means for reverse engineering.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Reduced pin count JTAG uses only two wires, a clock wire and a data wire.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] This is defined as part of the IEEE 1149.7 standard.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The two-wire interface reduced pressure on the number of pins, and devices can be connected in a star topology.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The star topology enables some parts of the system to be powered down, while others can still be accessed over JTAG; a daisy chain requires all JTAG interfaces to be powered.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Other two-wire interfaces exist, such as Serial Wire Debug (SWD) and Spy-Bi-Wire (SBW).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In JTAG, devices expose one or more *test access ports* (TAPs).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The picture above shows three TAPs, which might be individual chips or might be modules inside one chip.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] A daisy chain of TAPs is called a *scan chain*, or (loosely) a target.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Scan chains can be arbitrarily long, but in practice, twenty TAPs is unusually long.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] To use JTAG, a host is connected to the target's JTAG signals (TMS, TCK, TDI, TDO, etc.) through some kind of *JTAG adapter*, which may need to handle issues like level shifting and galvanic isolation.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The adapter connects to the host using some interface such as USB, PCI, Ethernet, and so forth.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The host communicates with the TAPs by manipulating TMS and TDI in conjunction with TCK and reading results through TDO (which is the only standard host-side input).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] At a basic level, using JTAG involves reading and writing instructions and their associated data registers, and sometimes involves running a number of test cycles.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Behind those registers is hardware that is not specified by JTAG, and which has its own states that are affected by JTAG activities.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Most JTAG hosts use the shortest path between two states, perhaps constrained by quirks of the adapter.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] (For example, one adapter only handles paths whose lengths are multiples of seven bits.) Some layers built on top of JTAG monitor the state transitions and use uncommon paths to trigger higher-level operations.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Some ARM cores use such sequences to enter and exit a two-wire (non-JTAG) SWD mode.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] A Zero Bit Scan (ZBS) sequence is used in IEEE 1149.7 to access advanced functionality such as switching TAPs into and out of scan chains, power management, and a different two-wire mode.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Instruction register sizes tend to be small, perhaps four or seven bits wide.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Except for BYPASS and EXTEST, all instruction opcodes are defined by the TAP implementer, as are their associated data registers; undefined instruction codes should not be used.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] On exit from the RESET state, the instruction register is preloaded with either BYPASS or IDCODE.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] This allows JTAG hosts to identify the size and, at least partially, contents of the scan chain to which they are connected.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] (They can enter the RESET state, then scan the Data Register until they read back the data they wrote.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] A BYPASS register has only a zero bit, while an IDCODE register is 32 bits and starts with a one.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] So the bits not written by the host can easily be mapped to TAPs.) Such identification is often used to sanity-check manual configuration since IDCODE is often nonspecific.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] It could, for example, identify an ARM Cortex-M3-based microcontroller, without specifying the microcontroller vendor or model; or a particular FPGA, but not how it has been programmed.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] A common idiom involves shifting BYPASS into the instruction registers of all TAPs except one, which receives some other instruction.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] That way, all TAPs except one expose a single-bit data register, and values can be selectively shifted into or out of that one TAP's data register without affecting any other TAP.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The IEEE 1149.1 (JTAG) standard describes a number of instructions to support boundary scan applications.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Some of these instructions are *mandatory*, but TAPs used for debug instead of boundary scan testing sometimes provide minimal or no support for these instructions.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Devices may define more instructions, and those definitions should be part of a BSDL file provided by the manufacturer.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The path creates a virtual access capability that circumvents the normal inputs and outputs, providing direct control of the device and detailed visibility for signals.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The contents of the boundary scan register, including signal I/O capabilities, are usually described by the manufacturer using a part-specific BSDL file.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] These are used with design 'netlists' from CAD/EDA systems to develop tests used in board manufacturing.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Commercial test systems often cost several thousand dollars for a complete system and include diagnostic options to pinpoint faults such as open circuits and shorts.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] They may also offer schematic or layout viewers to depict the fault in a graphical manner.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] To enable boundary scanning, IC vendors add logic to each of their devices, including scan cells for each of the signal pins.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] These cells are then connected together to form the boundary scan shift register (BSR), which is connected to a TAP controller.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] These designs are parts of most Verilog or VHDL libraries.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] An example helps show the operation of JTAG in real systems.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The example here is the debug TAP of an ARM11 processor, the ARM1136 core.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The processor itself has extensive JTAG capability, similar to what is found in other CPU cores, and it is integrated into chips with even more extensive capabilities accessed through JTAG.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] This is a non-trivial example, which is representative of a significant cross section of JTAG-enabled systems.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In addition, it shows how control mechanisms are built using JTAG's register read/write primitives, and how those combine to facilitate testing and debugging complex logic elements; CPUs are common, but FPGAs and ASICs include other complex elements which need to be debugged.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Licensees of this core integrate it into chips, usually combining it with other TAPs as well as numerous peripherals and memory.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] One of those other TAPs handles boundary scan testing for the whole chip; it is not supported by the debug TAP.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] That scan chain modification is one subject of a forthcoming IEEE 1149.7 standard.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] That model resembles the model used in other ARM cores.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Non-ARM systems generally have similar capabilities, perhaps implemented using the Nexus protocols on top of JTAG, or other vendor-specific schemes.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Older ARM7 and ARM9 cores include an *EmbeddedICE* module which combines most of those facilities, but has an awkward mechanism for instruction execution: the debugger must drive the CPU instruction pipeline, clock by clock, and directly access the data buses to read and write data to the CPU.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The ARM11 uses the same model for trace support (ETM, ETB) as those older cores.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Newer ARM Cortex cores closely resemble this debug model, but build on a *Debug Access Port* (DAP) instead of direct CPU access.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In this architecture (named *CoreSight Technology*), core and JTAG module is completely independent.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] They are also decoupled from JTAG so they can be hosted over ARM's two-wire **SWD** interface (see below) instead of just the six-wire JTAG interface.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] (ARM takes the four standard JTAG signals and adds the optional TRST, plus the RTCK signal used for adaptive clocking.) The CoreSight JTAG-DP is asynchronous to the core clocks, and does not implement RTCK.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Also, the newer cores have updated trace support.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] One basic way to debug software is to present a single-threaded model, where the debugger periodically stops execution of the program and examines its state as exposed by register contents and memory (including peripheral controller registers).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] When interesting program events approach, a person may want to single-step instructions (or lines of source code) to watch how a particular misbehavior happens.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] So, for example, a JTAG host might HALT the core, entering debug mode, and then read CPU registers using ITR and DCC.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] After saving processor state, it could write those registers with whatever values it needs, then execute arbitrary algorithms on the CPU, accessing memory and peripherals to help characterize the system state.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] After the debugger performs those operations, the state may be restored and execution continued using the RESTART instruction.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Debug mode is also entered asynchronously by the debug module, triggering a watchpoint or breakpoint, or by issuing a BKPT (breakpoint) instruction from the software being debugged.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] When it is not being used for instruction tracing, the ETM can also trigger entry to debug mode; it supports complex triggers sensitive to state and history, as well as the simple address comparisons exposed by the debug module.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Asynchronous transitions to debug mode are detected by polling the DSCR register.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] This is how single stepping is implemented: HALT the core, set a temporary breakpoint at the next instruction or next high-level statement, RESTART, poll DSCR until you detect asynchronous entry to debug state, remove that temporary breakpoint, repeat.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Modern software is often too complex to work well with such a single-threaded model.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] For example, a processor used to control a motor (perhaps one driving a saw blade) may not be able to safely enter halt mode; it may need to continue handling interrupts to ensure physical safety of people and/or machinery.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Issuing a HALT instruction using JTAG might be dangerous.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] ARM processors support an alternative debug mode, called *Monitor Mode*, to work with such situations.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] This monitor communicates with the debugger using the DCC and could arrange, for example, to single step only a single process while other processes (and interrupt handlers) continue running.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Microprocessor vendors have often defined their own core-specific debugging extensions.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Such vendors include Infineon, MIPS with EJTAG, and more.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] If the vendor does not adopt a standard (such as the ones used by ARM processors or Nexus), they need to define their own solution.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] If they support boundary scan, they generally build debugging over JTAG.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Freescale has COP and OnCE (On-Chip Emulation).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] OnCE includes a JTAG command which makes a TAP enter a special mode where the IR holds OnCE debugging commands for operations such as single stepping, breakpointing, and accessing registers or memory.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] It also defines EOnCE (Enhanced On-Chip Emulation) presented as addressing real-time concerns.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Note that tracing is non-invasive; systems do not need to stop operating to be traced.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Nexus defines a processor debug infrastructure that is largely vendor-independent.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] It also defines a high-speed auxiliary port interface, used for tracing and more.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Nexus is used with some newer platforms, such as the Atmel AVR32 and Freescale MPC5500 series processors.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The target's JTAG interface is accessed using some JTAG-enabled application and some JTAG adapter hardware.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] There is a wide range of such hardware, optimized for purposes such as production testing, debugging high-speed systems, low-cost microcontroller development, and so on.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] In the same way, the software used to drive such hardware can be quite varied.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Software developers mostly use JTAG for debugging and updating firmware.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] There are no official standards for JTAG adapter physical connectors.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Development boards usually include a header to support preferred development tools; in some cases, they include multiple such headers because they need to support multiple such tools.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] For example, a microcontroller, FPGA, and ARM application processor rarely share tools, so a development board using all of those components might have three or more headers.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Production boards may omit the headers, or when space is limited, may provide JTAG signal access using test points.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Those connectors tend to include more than just the four standardized signals (TMS, TCK, TDI, TDO).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Usually, reset signals are provided, one or both of TRST (TAP reset) and SRST (system reset).
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The connector usually provides the board-under-test's logic supply voltage so that the JTAG adapters use the appropriate logic levels.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The board voltage may also serve as a *board present* debugger input.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Other event input or output signals may be provided, or general purpose I/O (GPIO) lines, to support more complex debugging architectures.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Higher end products frequently use dense connectors (frequently 38-pin MICTOR connectors) to support high-speed tracing in conjunction with JTAG operations.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] A recent trend is to have development boards integrate a USB interface to JTAG, where a second channel is used for a serial port.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] (Smaller boards can also be powered through USB.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Since modern PCs tend to omit serial ports, such integrated debug links can significantly reduce clutter for developers.) Production boards often rely on bed-of-nails connections to test points for testing and programming.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] There are both *dumb* adapters, where the host decides and performs all JTAG operations; and *smart* ones, where some of that work is performed inside the adapter, often driven by a microcontroller.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] The *smart* adapters eliminate link latencies for operation sequences that may involve polling for status changes between steps, and may accordingly offer higher throughput.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] As of 2018, adapters with a USB link from the host are the most common approach.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Higher-end products often support Ethernet, with the advantage that the debug host can be quite remote.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Adapters that support high-speed trace ports generally include several megabytes of trace buffer and provide high-speed links (USB or Ethernet) to get that data to the host.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Parallel port adapters are simple and inexpensive, but they are relatively slow because they use the host CPU to change each bit ("bit banging").
[src:scan-chain/jtag] They have declined in usefulness because most computers in recent years don't have a parallel port.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Driver support is also a problem because pin usage by adapters varies widely.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Since the parallel port is based on 5 V logic level, most adapters lacked voltage translation support for 3.3 V or 1.8 V target voltages.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] RS-232 serial port adapters also exist and are similarly declining in usefulness.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] They generally involve either slower bit banging than a parallel port or a microcontroller translating some command protocol to JTAG operations.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Such serial adapters are also not fast, but their command protocols could generally be reused on top of higher-speed links.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] With all JTAG adapters, software support is a basic concern.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Some vendors do not publish the protocols used by their JTAG adapter hardware, limiting their customers to the tool chains supported by those vendors.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] This is a particular issue for "smart" adapters, some of which embed significant amounts of knowledge about how to interact with specific CPUs.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Most development environments for embedded software include JTAG support.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] All such software tends to include basic debugger support: stopping, halting, single stepping, breakpoints, data structure browsing, and so on.
[src:scan-chain/jtag] Commercial tools tend to provide tools like very accurate simulators and trace analysis, which are not currently available as open source.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] The basic structure of scan include the following set of signals in order to control and observe the scan mechanism.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] A scan enable (SE) pin is a special signal that is added to a design.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] When this signal is asserted, every flip-flop in the design is connected into a long shift register.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] Clock signal which is used for controlling all the flip-flops in the chain during shift phase and the capture phase.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] An arbitrary pattern can be entered into the chain of flip-flops, and the state of every flip-flop can be read out.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] The conceptual origins of scan date back to the 1965, notably with IBM’s System/360 Model 50, which implemented scan-in and scan-out functions for processor self-diagnosis.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] Scan design, as formally applied to VLSI testing, gained traction after the landmark 1973 paper by Williams and Angell, and was widely advanced by IBM researchers including Eichelberger and Williams.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] In a full scan design, automatic test pattern generation (ATPG) is particularly simple.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] No sequential pattern generation is required - combinatorial tests, which are much easier to generate, will suffice.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] If you have a combinatorial test, it can be easily applied.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] In a chip that does not have a full scan design—i.e., the chip has sequential circuits, such as memory elements that are not part of the scan chain, sequential pattern generation is required.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] Test pattern generation for sequential circuits searches for a sequence of vectors to detect a particular fault through the space of all possible vector sequences.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] Even a simple stuck-at fault requires a sequence of vectors for detection in a sequential circuit.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] Also, due to the presence of memory elements, the controllability and observability of the internal signals in a sequential circuit are in general much more difficult than those in a combinational logic circuit.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] These factors make the complexity of sequential ATPG much higher than that of combinational ATPG.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] Modern Electronic Design Automation (EDA) tools fully support scan insertion, rule checking, and ATPG vector generation.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] Scan design audits ensure compliance with DFT rules — such as using only D-type flip-flops, clock controllability, and separating scan and functional clocks.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] Once design verification is complete, automatic scan insertion tools can retrofit flip-flops, wire scan chains, and generate test vectors with high fault coverage.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] Scan testing is especially critical in **ASICs and SoCs**, where internal nodes are otherwise unobservable.
[src:scan-chain/scan-chain] Despite area and timing costs, scan design remains the industry standard for testability and is supported by all major digital design flows.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] A **stuck-at fault** is a particular fault model used by fault simulators and automatic test pattern generation (ATPG) tools to mimic a manufacturing defect within an integrated circuit.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] Individual signals and pins are assumed to be *stuck* at Logical '1', '0' and 'X'.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] For example, an input is tied to a logical 1 state during test generation to assure that a manufacturing defect with that type of behavior can be found with a specific test pattern.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] Likewise the input could be tied to a logical 0 to model the behavior of a defective circuit that cannot switch its output pin.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] Not all faults can be analyzed using the stuck-at fault model.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] Compensation for static hazards, namely branching signals, can render a circuit untestable using this model.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] Also, redundant circuits cannot be tested using this model, since by design there is no change in any output as a result of a single fault.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] Sequential circuits which contain storage.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] This fault model applies to gate level circuits, or a block of a sequential circuit which can be separated from the storage elements.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] Ideally a gate-level circuit would be completely tested by applying all possible inputs and checking that they gave the right outputs, but this is completely impractical: an adder to add two 32-bit numbers would require 264 = 1.8*1019 tests, taking 58 years at 0.1 ns/test.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] The *stuck at* fault model assumes that only one input on one gate will be faulty at a time, assuming that if more are faulty, a test that can detect any single fault, should easily find multiple faults.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] To use this fault model, each input pin on each gate in turn, is assumed to be grounded, and a *test vector* is developed to indicate the circuit is faulty.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] The test vector is a collection of bits to apply to the circuit's inputs, and a collection of bits expected at the circuit's output.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] If the gate pin under consideration is grounded, and this test vector is applied to the circuit, at least one of the output bits will not agree with the corresponding output bit in the test vector.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] After obtaining the test vectors for grounded pins, each pin is connected in turn to a logic one and another set of test vectors is used to find faults occurring under these conditions.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] Each of these faults is called a single *stuck-at-0* (s-a-0) or a single *stuck-at-1* (s-a-1) fault, respectively.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] While the same testing model works moderately well for CMOS, it is not able to detect all possible CMOS faults.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] This is because CMOS may experience a failure mode known as a *stuck-open* fault, which cannot be reliably detected with one test vector and requires that two vectors be applied sequentially.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] The model also fails to detect bridging faults between adjacent signal lines, occurring in pins that drive bus connections and array structures.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] Nevertheless, the concept of single stuck-at faults is widely used, and with some additional tests has allowed industry to ship an acceptable low number of bad circuits.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] A series of tests for stuck-at faults will often, purely by serendipity, find a large number of other faults, such as stuck-open faults.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] This is sometimes called "windfall" fault coverage.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] Another type of testing called *IDDQ testing* measures the way the power supply current of a CMOS integrated circuit changes when a small number of slowly changing test vectors are applied.
[src:scan-chain/stuck-at-fault] Since CMOS draws a very low current when its inputs are static, any increase in that current indicates a potential problem.
